T1  - Excessive estradiol secretion in polycystic ovarian disease.
T3  - Comment in: Am J Obstet Gynecol. 1994 Dec;171(6):1673<ovid:br/> PMID: 7695722 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7695722]
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/0002-9378(93)90286-r
A1  - Benjamin, F
A1  - Toles, A W
A1  - Seltzer, V L
A1  - Deutsch, S
Y1  - 1993//
N1  - Comment in (CIN)
N2  - Polycystic ovarian disease is both a hyperestrogenic and a hyperandrogenic syndrome, and all studies have shown that hyperestrogenemia is the result of an elevation of estrone with plasma estradiol levels in the normal follicular range. Because a literature search failed to reveal any report of polycystic ovarian disease with significantly elevated estradiol levels, we report a case in which the plasma estradiol was so massively elevated as to mimic an estrogen-producing neoplasm. This case also suggests that although polycystic ovarian disease is a very rare cause of such excessive estradiol production, it should be included in the differential diagnosis of estrogen-producing neoplasms.
